> People judge sequence randomness by looking for the longest streak of identical outcomes, perceiving sequences where the longest streak takes up a smaller proportion of the sequence length as more random.

I then translated this into `candidate.py`, keeping the implementation strictly aligned to the one mechanism (avoidance of long streaks). The single cognitive parameter `tau` determines the sensitivity to this feature, and it uses `max_run_norm` to ensure scale invariance across sequence lengths. The code correctly limits the deterministic probability bound between `[1e-6, 1 - 1e-6]` ensuring no likelihood evaluations result in NaN or `-inf`. 

